,Recommended,302080,13978877,"Posted: 13 January, 2015",all,Old Man Ganksalot,"Does exactly what it says on the tin.ProsDrive busesSelect from a variety of busesIncrease in difficulty as more routes are completedSignal lights have a functionCan be modded with the right tools and knowledgeRealistic screams from passengers during crashes or sudden breakingConsCould use a hardcore bus driver mode (gas usage, aggressive drivers, etc.)I believe the only song in the game is played at the title screen, and it's not ""The Wheels on the Bus""No Steam Workshop supportAbsolute perfection for what it is. Does not strive to be something it is clearly not. Stays within the boundaries of the genre while managing to be fresh.If you are looking to drive buses, this is the game to do it. If you are not looking to drive buses, this game is clearly not for you and you should look for games that cater to people with poor taste (such as yourself)."
,Recommended,302080,11684131,"Posted: 12 August, 2014",all,Angoratatouille,"Even though it's mission-based instead of open-world (like ETS2, which I love), I'm enjoying this one!  It's not for everyone, as the game is rather slow-paced and requires concentration rather than quick reflexes.The graphics are dated, but they look nice for what they are, and the game does run in full HD. The city (and suburbs) we're driving in for the missions is large and detailed. There are weather effects like snow, rain, storms, and I personally found that snow-covered roads do affect the driving slightly.The game runs flawlessly on my Win7 64-bit system with an AMD Radeon card. I'm using an XBox 360 game controller, which I had no trouble configuring (doesn't recognize the D-pad, but the rest works fine)."
