76561198353187264,Recommended,302080,28823814,"Posted: 30 December, 2016",all,troyski72,"While it may be good value for money, Bus Driver is a very basic bus simulator with very random locations and bus routes.The world map contains different areas for the bus routes to be taking place in. Their names are very random, as for whatever reason, SCS Software has named bus stops as towns in Greater London, and as a Londoner, it is a negative, as they look nothing like their real life counterpart. For instance, a bus route has Beckton a bus stop away from Eltham which realistically, they are on either side of the River ThamesMost bus routes are short or are long distance with routes having only 5 stops or long distances with no stops. Many buses have similar routes as there are 5 routes that operate around the Grove Park and Hounslow/ Ewell area.You can only operate a bus route in one direction, with no variation of passengers, weather or traffic, making each playthrough of a bus route the same.The game includes 5 different buses with two buses having a different colour scheme. They are, except for the double decker, American buses, so you'll be driving in the right side od the road. They look ok, but there isn't a cab view or the ability of exit the bus or free roam, so the game is very linear. There are also two coaches, school bus and a prison bus.The game was originally released in 2007 with 5 tiers. There are 6 routes for each tier, making this Bus Driver include 36 routes. You could fly through the game in less than an hour, as to pass a teir, 4 routes need to be completed.Graphically, there has been alot of backlash and nowadays, it looks quite poor, but for 2007, it's good.The game overall is very basic, geographically incorrect and very short. I'd still recommend it as it was my first bus simulatior almost 10 years ago and is good for beginners and value.6/10 Only due to its easy accessibility for beginners."
